        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Reports Overview",
            Slug = "reports-overview",
            Summary = "How to build and run reports: pick what to report on, choose columns and filters, chart the results, and use the ready-made reports and flow diagrams.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/reports"]""",
            Tags = """["reports","analytics","charts","export"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Reports Overview\n\nReports is where you answer questions about your business. It gives you two ways to work: 28 ready-made reports for common questions, and a builder for making your own report on any part of your data.\n\n### Three Parts of the Reports Page\n\nThe Reports page has three parts, reached from the top navigation:\n\n1. **Ready-Made Reports** — The page you land on. A list on the left holds 28 reports grouped by topic (production, money, personal, quality, and more). Click one to see its chart and table. Reports that use a date range show date pickers at the top.\n\n2. **Build Your Own** — Make a custom report. Pick what to report on (like Jobs, Parts, or Invoices), choose columns, add filters, group and sort, then run it. Results show as a table, with a chart if you want one. Save your report to use again.\n\n3. **Flow Diagrams** — Pictures that show how work moves through your business: Quote to Cash, Job Stage Flow, Material to Product, Worker Orders, Expense Flow, Vendor Supply Chain, Quality Rejection, Inventory Location, Customer Revenue, and Training Completion.\n\n### Pre-Built Report Templates (28)\n\nThe pre-built reports cover every major domain:\n\n**Production & Operations:**\n- **Jobs by Stage** — Bar chart showing how many jobs are in each stage\n- **Overdue Jobs** — Table of jobs past their due date\n- **Job Completion Trend** — Line chart of jobs completed over time\n- **On-Time Delivery** — Percentage of jobs delivered on or before due date\n- **Average Lead Time** — Average days from job creation to completion by track type\n- **Time in Stage** — How long jobs spend in each stage\n- **Job Margin** — Revenue vs. cost analysis per job\n- **Cycle Review** — Planning cycle performance summary\n- **R&D Report** — R&D/tooling track activity and outcomes\n\n**People & Time:**\n- **Time by User** — Hours logged per team member (date range required)\n- **Team Workload** — Current job assignments per user\n- **Employee Productivity** — Output metrics per employee\n- **My Work History** — Personal job completion history\n- **My Time Log** — Personal time entries\n- **My Cycle Summary** — Personal planning cycle performance\n- **My Expense History** — Personal expense submissions\n\n**Sales & Financial:**\n- **Expense Summary** — Spending by category\n- **Lead Pipeline** — Lead counts by status\n- **Customer Activity** — Customer engagement metrics\n- **AR Aging** — Outstanding receivables by aging bucket\n- **Revenue** — Revenue over time\n- **Profit & Loss** — Simple income vs. expenses\n- **Quote-to-Close** — Quote conversion rates and timelines\n- **Lead-to-Sales** — Lead conversion funnel\n\n**Logistics & Quality:**\n- **Shipping Summary** — Shipment volume and carrier usage\n- **Inventory Levels** — Current stock quantities\n- **Maintenance** — Asset maintenance activity and costs\n- **Quality/Scrap** — Scrap rates and quality inspection results\n\n### Building Your Own Report\n\nBuilding your own report puts you in charge of what data you see and how it looks.\n\n**Step 1 — Pick What to Report On:** Choose from 28 kinds of data. Each one offers its own columns. They include Jobs, Parts, Customers, Expenses, Time Entries, Invoices, Leads, Assets, Purchase Orders, Sales Orders, Quotes, Shipments, Inventory, Payments, Vendors, Production Runs, Lot Records, QC Inspections, Maintenance Schedules and Logs, Downtime Logs, Customer Returns, Bin Movements, Planning Cycles, and the line items on invoices, sales orders, purchase orders, and quotes.\n\n**Step 2 — Choose Columns:** Check the columns you want in the results. Each kind of data has its own set, and many pull in related details too — like the customer's name on a job, or the vendor's name on a purchase order.\n\n**Step 3 — Add Filters:** Narrow the results. Each filter is a field, a comparison, and a value — for example, Status is Open, or Amount is more than 100. You can add as many filters as you need.\n\n**Step 4 — Group & Sort:** You can group results by a shared value (like status, date, or category) and sort by any column, low to high or high to low.\n\n**Step 5 — Turn It Into a Chart:** Choose a chart: bar, line, pie, doughnut, or just a table. For a chart, pick what labels each part (like a category) and what number sets its size (like an amount).\n\n**Run and Save:** Click Run Report to see the results in a table below your settings. Save the report with a name, an optional note, and a switch for whether others can see it. Saved reports show up in a menu for quick reuse.\n\n### Chart Types\n\nBoth ready-made reports and reports you build can show a chart:\n\n- **Bar charts** — Compare amounts side by side (jobs by stage, time by user, expenses by category)\n- **Line charts** — Show trends over time (completion trend, revenue, lead time)\n- **Pie charts** — Show how a whole splits into parts (lead pipeline, expense breakdown)\n- **Doughnut charts** — Like a pie, good for status breakdowns\n- **Flow diagrams** — Show how data moves from one stage to the next\n\nCharts let you click to focus: click a bar or slice to narrow the table below to just that piece. Click again to see everything.\n\n### Ways to Save or Share\n\n- **CSV** — After running a report, click CSV to download the results as a spreadsheet file you can open in Excel.\n- **PDF** — Download a tidy, formatted PDF of the report.\n- **Print** — Print the report; the menus and controls drop away so only the report itself prints.\n\n### Who Can Use Reports\n\nThe full Reports page is for Admins, Managers, Office Managers, and PMs. Engineers and Production Workers don't have it, but they can still see their own personal reports (My Work History, My Time Log, My Expense History) from their own pages.\n\n### Saved Reports\n\nA saved report remembers everything you set up: the data you chose, your columns, filters, grouping, sorting, and chart. You can share it with everyone who can see reports, or keep it just for yourself. Open a saved report from the menu to view it, change it, or delete it.","sections":[]}"""
        });

